@section Macro transfomrers


Macro transformers are procedures you can use in a @syntax{define-syntax} context to register a
procedure that can transform S--expressions into other S--expressions.  Only use these when we need
to break hygiene in a controlled way; for many use cases @syntax{syntax-rules} is more appropriate,
as it offers stronger guarantees of hygiene, is more high--level and is standard @rnrs{5} Scheme.

For those situations where you need more control, however, @chicken{} supports two kinds of
low--level macros: so--called explicit renaming and implicit renaming macros.

@menu
* syntax trans explicit::       Explicit renaming macros.
* syntax trans implicit::       Implicit renaming macros.
@end menu

@c page
@node syntax trans explicit
@subsection Explicit renaming macros


The low--level macro facility that @chicken{} provides is called ``explicit renaming'' and allows
writing hygienic or non--hygienic macros procedurally.  When given a return value of the one of the
procedures @func{er-macro-transformer} or @func{ir-macro-transformer} instead of a
@syntax{syntax-rules} form, @syntax{define-syntax} evaluates the procedure in a distinct expansion
environment (initially having access to the exported identifiers of the @library{scheme} module).
The procedure takes an expression and two other arguments and returns a transformed expression.

For example, the transformation procedure for a @syntax{call} macro such that @code{(call proc arg
...)} expands into @code{(proc arg ...)} can be written as:

@lisp
(er-macro-transformer
  (lambda (exp rename compare)
    (cdr exp)))
@end lisp

Expressions are represented as lists in the traditional manner, except that identifiers are
represented as special uninterned symbols.

The second argument to a transformation procedure is a renaming procedure that takes the
representation of an identifier as its argument and returns the representation of a fresh identifier
that occurs nowhere else in the program.  For example, the transformation procedure for a simplified
version of the @syntax{let} macro might be written as:

@lisp
(er-macro-transformer
  (lambda (exp rename compare)
    (let ((vars  (map car  (cadr exp)))
          (inits (map cadr (cadr exp)))
          (body  (cddr exp)))
      `((lambda ,vars ,@@body)
        ,@@inits))))
@end lisp

This would not be hygienic, however.  A hygienic @syntax{let} macro must rename the identifier
@syntax{lambda} to protect it from being captured by a local binding.  The renaming effectively
creates a fresh alias for @syntax{lambda}, one that cannot be captured by any subsequent binding:

@lisp
(er-macro-transformer
  (lambda (exp rename compare)
    (let ((vars  (map car  (cadr exp)))
          (inits (map cadr (cadr exp)))
          (body  (cddr exp)))
      `((,(rename 'lambda) ,vars ,@@body)
        ,@@inits))))
@end lisp

The expression returned by the transformation procedure will be expanded in the syntactic
environment obtained from the syntactic environment of the macro application by binding any fresh
identifiers generated by the renaming procedure to the denotations of the original identifiers in
the syntactic environment in which the macro was defined.  This means that a renamed identifier will
denote the same thing as the original identifier unless the transformation procedure that renamed
the identifier placed an occurrence of it in a binding position.

Identifiers obtained from any two calls to the renaming procedure with the same argument will
necessarily be the same, but will denote the same syntactical binding.  It is an error if the
renaming procedure is called after the transformation procedure has returned.

The third argument to a transformation procedure is a comparison predicate that takes the
representations of two identifiers as its arguments and returns true if and only if they denote the
same thing in the syntactic environment that will be used to expand the transformed macro
application.  For example, the transformation procedure for a simplified version of the
@syntax{cond} macro can be written as:

@lisp
(er-macro-transformer
  (lambda (exp rename compare)
    (let ((clauses (cdr exp)))
      (if (null? clauses)
          `(,(rename 'quote) unspecified)
          (let* ((first (car clauses))
                 (rest  (cdr clauses))
                 (test  (car first)))
            (cond ((and (symbol? test)
                        (compare test (rename 'else)))
                   `(,(rename 'begin) ,@@(cdr first)))
                  (else `(,(rename 'if) ,test
                             (,(rename 'begin) ,@@(cdr first))
                           (,(r 'cond) ,@@rest)))))))))
@end lisp

In this example the identifier @syntax{else} is renamed before being passed to the comparison
predicate, so the comparison will be true if and only if the test expression is an identifier that
denotes the same thing in the syntactic environment of the expression being transformed as
@syntax{else} denotes in the syntactic environment in which the @syntax{cond} macro was defined.  If
@syntax{else} were not renamed before being passed to the comparison predicate, then it would match
a local variable that happened to be named @syntax{else}, and the macro would not be hygienic.  The
final recursive call to @syntax{cond} also needs to be renamed because someone might create an alias
for this macro and use it in a @syntax{let} where @syntax{cond} is an ordinary variable.

Some macros are non--hygienic by design.  For example, the following defines a @syntax{loop} macro
that implicitly binds @func{exit} to an escape procedure.  The binding of @func{exit} is intended to
capture free references to @func{exit} in the body of the loop, so @func{exit} is not renamed.

@lisp
(define-syntax loop
  (er-macro-transformer
    (lambda (x r c)
      (let ((body (cdr x)))
        `(,(r 'call-with-current-continuation)
          (,(r 'lambda) (exit)
           (,(r 'let) ,(r 'f) () ,@@body (,(r 'f)))))))))
@end lisp

Suppose a @syntax{while} macro is implemented using @syntax{loop}, with the intent that
@syntax{exit} may be used to escape from the @syntax{while} loop.  The @syntax{while} macro cannot
be written as:

@lisp
(define-syntax while
  (syntax-rules ()
    ((while test body ...)
     (loop (if (not test) (exit #f))
           body ...))))
@end lisp

@noindent
because the reference to @func{exit} that is inserted by the @syntax{while} macro is intended to be
captured by the binding of @func{exit} that will be inserted by the @syntax{loop} macro.  In other
words, this @syntax{while} macro is not hygienic.  Like @syntax{loop}, it must be written
procedurally:

@lisp
(define-syntax while
  (er-macro-transformer
    (lambda (x r c)
      (let ((test (cadr x))
            (body (cddr x)))
        `(,(r 'loop)
          (,(r 'if) (,(r 'not) ,test) (exit #f))
          ,@@body)))))
@end lisp

Think about it: If we @strong{did} rename @func{exit}, it would refer to an @func{exit} procedure
existing in the context of the macro's definition.  That one @strong{actually exists}; it is the
procedure that exits the Scheme interpreter.  Definitely @strong{not} the one we want.  So now we
make it refer to an @func{exit} that's locally bound in the environment where the macro is expanded.

@strong{NOTE} This implementation of explicit-renaming macros allows passing arbitrary expressions
to the renaming and comparison procedures.  When being renamed, a fresh copy of the expression will
be produced, with all identifiers renamed appropriately.  Comparison also supports arbitrary
expressions as arguments.


@defun er-macro-transformer @var{transformer}
Returns an explicit--renaming macro transformer procedure created from the procedural macro body
@var{transformer}, which is a procedure of three arguments.

This procedure will be called on expansion with the complete S--expression of the macro invocation,
a rename procedure that hygienically renames identifiers and a comparison procedure that compares
(possibly renamed) identifiers.

Implementation note: this procedure currently just returns its argument unchanged and is available
for writing low--level macros in a more portable fashion, without hard--coding the signature of a
transformer procedure.
@end defun

