@subsection Implicit renaming macros


Explicit renaming macros generally require the user to perform quite a few renames, because most
identifiers that aren't taken from the input expression should generally be inserted hygienically.
It would make more sense to give the output expression as--is, and only explicitly convert those
identifiers that you want to treat as @strong{unhygienic}.

This can be done with implicit renaming macros.  They just swap the default insertion ``mode'' from
unhygienic to hygienic, so to speak.  Here's the @syntax{cond} example from the previous section as
an ir--macro:

@lisp
(ir-macro-transformer
  (lambda (exp inject compare)
    (let ((clauses (cdr exp)))
      (if (null? clauses)
          `(quote unspecified)
          (let* ((first (car clauses))
                 (rest (cdr clauses))
                 (test (car first)))
            (cond ((and (symbol? test)
                        (compare test 'else))
                   `(begin ,@@(cdr first)))
                  (else `(if ,test
                             (begin ,@@(cdr first))
                             (cond ,@@rest)))))))))
@end lisp

In this example the identifier @syntax{else} does @strong{not} need to be renamed before being
passed to the comparison predicate because it is already @strong{implicitly} renamed.  This
comparison will also be true if and only if the test expression is an identifier that denotes the
same thing in the syntactic environment of the expression being transformed as @syntax{else} denotes
in the syntactic environment in which the @syntax{cond} macro was defined.  If @syntax{else} were
not renamed before being passed to the comparison predicate, then it would match a local variable
that happened to be named @syntax{else}, and the macro would not be hygienic.

As you can see, the code is a lot clearer because it isn't obscured by excessive renaming.

Here's the @syntax{loop} macro so you can see how hygiene can be broken with implicit renaming macros:

@lisp
(define-syntax loop
  (ir-macro-transformer
    (lambda (expr inject compare)
      (let ((body (cdr expr)))
        `(call-with-current-continuation
          (lambda (,(inject 'exit))
           (let f () ,@@body (f))))))))
@end lisp

The @syntax{while} macro is a little trickier: do we inject the call to @func{exit} or not?  Just
like the explicit renaming macro version did @strong{not} rename it, we must inject it to allow it
to be captured by the @syntax{loop} macro:

@lisp
(define-syntax while
  (ir-macro-transformer
    (lambda (expr inject compare)
      (let ((test (cadr expr))
            (body (cddr expr)))
        `(loop
          (if (not ,test) (,(inject 'exit) #f))
          ,@@body)))))
@end lisp

@strong{NOTE} Just like explicit renaming macros, this implementation of implicit renaming macros
allow passing arbitrary expressions to the injection and comparison procedures.  The injection
procedure also return fresh copies of its input.


@defun ir-macro-transformer @var{transformer}
This procedure accepts a @strong{reverse} syntax transformer, also known as an @strong{implicit
renaming macro transformer}.  This is a transformer which works almost like
@func{er-macro-transformer}, except the rename and compare procedures it receives work a little
differently.

The rename procedure is now called @code{inject} and instead of renaming the identifier to be
resolved in the macro's definition environment, it will explicitly @strong{inject} the identifier to
be resolved in the expansion environment.  Any non--injected identifiers in the output expression
produced by the transformer will be implicitly renamed to refer to the macro's environment instead.
All identifiers in the input expression are of course implicitly injected just like with explicit
renaming macros.  See the section above for a more complete explanation.

To compare an input identifier you can generally compare to the bare symbol and only free
identifiers will match.  In practice, this means that when you would call e.g.:

@lisp
(compare (cadr expression) (rename 'x))
@end lisp

@noindent
in an explicit--renaming macro, you simply call:

@lisp
(compare (cadr expression) 'x)
@end lisp

@noindent
in the implicit--renaming macro.  Likewise, an @strong{unhygienic} explicit--renaming macro's
comparison:

@lisp
(compare sym 'abc)
@end lisp

@noindent
should be written as @code{(compare sym (inject 'abc))} in an implicit--renaming macro.
@end defun

