@node syntax helpers
@section Macro helper procedures


@deffn Syntax begin-for-syntax @qvar{exp} @dots{}
Equivalent to:

@lisp
(begin @qvar{exp} @dots{})
@end lisp

@noindent
but performs the evaluation of the expression during macro--expansion time, using the macro
environment rather than the interaction environment.  We can use this to define our own helper
procedures that we can call from a syntax transformer.
@end deffn


@deffn Syntax define-for-syntax (@qvar{name} @qvar{var} ...) @var{exp} @dots{}
@deffnx Syntax define-for-syntax (@qvar{name} @qvari{var} @dots{} @qvarn{var} . @qvarn1{var}) @qvari{exp} @dots{}
@deffnx Syntax define-for-syntax @qvar{name}
@deffnx Syntax define-for-syntax @qvar{name} @qvar{value}
Define the toplevel variable @qvar{name} at macro--expansion time.  This can be helpful when we want
to define support procedures for use in macro--transformers, for example.

Essentially, this is a shorthand for:

@lisp
(begin-for-syntax (define ...))
@end lisp

Note that @syntax{define-for-syntax} definitions within a module are implicitly added to that
module's import library.  Refer to the documentation on @emph{import libraries} for more
information.
@end deffn


@defun syntax @var{expression}
Quote the @var{expression} for use in a syntax expansion.  Any syntactic information will be
stripped from the @var{expression}.
@end defun


@defun strip-syntax @var{expression}
Strip all syntactical information from @var{expression}, returning a new expression where symbols
have all context--information removed.

We should use this procedure whenever we want to manually construct new identifiers, which an
unhygienic macro can insert.  In some cases it does not @strong{appear} to be necessary to strip
context information when we use the macro, but we still should do it.  Sometimes identifiers will
not have been renamed (most often at top--level), but there may be other contexts in which
identifiers @strong{will} have been renamed.
@end defun


@defun get-line-number @var{expr}
If @var{expr} is a pair with the car being a symbol, and line--number information is available for
this expression, then this procedure returns the associated source file and line number as a string.
If line--number information is not available, then @false{} is returned.  Note that line--number
information for expressions is only available in the compiler.
@end defun


@defun syntax-error @var{message} @var{argument} @dots{}
@defunx syntax-error @var{location} @var{message} @var{argument} @dots{}
Signal an exception of the kind @code{(exn syntax)}.  Otherwise identical to @func{error}.
@end defun

