@node syntax compiler
@section Compiler macros


@deffn Syntax define-compiler-syntax @qvar{name}
@deffnx Syntax define-compiler-syntax @qvar{name} @qvar{transformer}
Define what is usually called a @strong{compiler macro} in Lisp: @qvar{name} should be the name of a
globally or locally bound procedure.  Any direct call to this procedure will be transformed before
compilation, which allows arbitrary rewritings of function calls.

@qvar{transformer} can be a @syntax{syntax-rules} expression or a transformer procedure (as returned
by @func{er-macro-transformer} or @func{ir-macro-transformer}).  Returning the original form in an
explicit/implicit--renaming macro or simply ``falling trough'' all patterns in a
@syntax{syntax-rules} form will keep the original expression and compile it normally.

In the interpreter this form does nothing and returns an unspecified value.

A compiler--syntax is always local to the current compilation unit and can not be exported.  A
compiler--syntax defined inside a module is not visible outside of that module.

@syntax{define-compiler-syntax} should only be used at top--level.  Local compiler--syntax can be
defined with @syntax{let-compiler-syntax}.

@lisp
(define-compiler-syntax +
  (syntax-rules ()
    ((_)        1)
    ((_ ?x 0)   ?x)))
@end lisp

If no transformer is given, then @code{(define-compiler-syntax @qvar{name})} removes any
compiler--syntax definitions for @qvar{name}.
@end deffn


@deffn Syntax let-compiler-syntax ((@qvar{name} [@qvar{transformer}]) @dots{}) @qvar{body} @dots{}
Allow the definition local compiler macros, which are only applicable inside @qvar{body}.  By not
providing a @var{transformer} expression, compiler--syntax for specific identifiers can be
temporarily disabled.
@end deffn

